He did work connecting with the wood. The washing machines in those days had wooden rollers. And he understood wood. He'd had an old uncle who had taught him a bit of chair making, they never followed it as an occupation. At least not that my mother ev
er said. He might have done a bit in his youth, but he understood - through this old uncle - the handle of wood and the look of wood, he could tell you - what it was and which was well seasoned, which was not. And - his knowledge of wood - got him this jo
b where he made - wood rollers for washing machines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 They made a lot of wringers didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 It - it was practically the main - work at that time, the main occupation was - was wringers. Yes. Mind there were two Summer}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7737737\charrsid15471180 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 scales but they were branc
hes of the same family, one was Carrow Lane and one was along Pitt Street or - what they. Park - Parkwood, along there. But my father worked in the one in Connor Lane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 I've seen a photograph of the old railway in Keighley in about 1910.
