n or something like that. It was - it wasn't the Wide Wide World. But she'd two of these, and one was nature, I've forgotten what the other was. 'Cos there were fishes in this - we got a lot of - that kind of knowledge - from those books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Did you have a lot of novels about the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 
Penny novels occa - once a week mother got. Penny novels. We didn't have any - what we'd call good novels, not the Brontes or those. Not in those years. You see, the free library hadn't 
come. After the free library came then - we brought books into the house from the free library but that was at Beechcliffe. Because it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 And books were too expensive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 To buy, that kind of book. If anybody lent one, you know, occasionally passed 
one on and - what did father used to bring, some - oh those were comics. Something that other men brought to the works and passed on and he brought home. And me brother got the Boys Friend. And me mother got this penny - woman's - Life or Woman's somethin
g - once a week. And - we got the books we got at Christmas. And - I don't remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 What sort of books would they have been, the ones that you got at Christmas? Would they be fairy stories and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Yes - they'd be - yes, fairy stor
ies and - I had a book up there that was - animals and birds. I'll tell you what - what was I going to say - we got Sunday school prizes, which were books. Yes, for going to Sunday school. Those were - what I call proper books. You know, suitable to our a
ge, and of course we all read them, if it was me brother's prize I read it, there's no doubt about it, whether I had to let him catch me reading it or not. I had to hand it over if he came in, I had - hadn't to - I hadn't first go at it you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 So you were quite keen readers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Keen readers, yes. I was and my brother was. But not this second sister. She wasn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 She was a singer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Yes. Mm. More like - she was - more for - going out to be - you see she was one to go out and play when she w
as young, and - she'd go out to somebody's house if she was invited you know, and have a sing song, but she wasn't one who sat much to read a book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 What sort of newspapers did you get if any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 We got one, we got - well eventually it became the - 
it - we got the Keighley News but - my father had got the Craven Herald, when he was - at - Silsden, you see, and - when we came to Keighley - there was - he was still going to have the Craven Herald, but there was another one and I think they called that
 the Keighley Herald. There was another one, it wasn't - it wasn't the Keighley News.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 It became the Keighley News presumably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Well we - we were taking the Keighley News after but I think that newspaper came to an end. Mm. It was in opposition, ye
s, there was another Keighley paper. So - I think it would be the Keighley Herald. As distinct from the Craven Herald.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Your mother got a magazine and your brother got a magazine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Were there any other magazines bought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 No, not at that time, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Do you remember your mother or father reading just quietly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 
Do you mean to themselves? Without talking. Yes. Yes, fath - father read a book - and - it's still in existence, I think it must have been lent to him. I do
n't remember it - staying with us, and that was Walterton's Wanderings in South America. Walterton's, a man called Waltert}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7737737\charrsid15471180 on was one of the first - explo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 rers of the Amazon. It was the Amazon chiefly, and - that was the kind of thing that he was - very keen
 on, anything to do with nature - he wasn't - he wasn't a man who'd want to read what you call blood and thunders at all, he wouldn't have any time for them at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 He was always interested in geography and nature?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Yes, and nature, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 
They would read - they would read aloud the books that were given us Christmas presents. Whether it was to us or the younger children. It - it wasn't a great feature - of the home. But - still they woul
d do, yes, well there would be no point in buying a child a book if - if it couldn't read it you see, they'd have to read it. As soon as we were old enough we'd have to read for the young ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 You did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Yes, oh yes, we'd do that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13525481 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5131904 OS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10517864\charrsid15471180 Not up to that age. Not up to fo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7737737\charrsid15471180 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
